{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":25357,"record_hash":"sha256:0cbd3aa0d737680e71c133af6f700acd4ad64c1ed13e7cbd9dd50bfce18e4385","timestamp":"2026-05-11T09:53:35.935Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"user","text":"<subagent_notification>\n{\"agent_path\":\"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"status\":{\"completed\":\"**Findings**\\n\\n- **P2 Atomicity gap at the real caller.** [gitmeta.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:71) commits session index/schema/source metadata before the batched `handle.apply_edits(...)` at [gitmeta.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:104). If the batch fails, GitMeta has already recorded a session/source without the transcript and record-hash set. The new `MetaEdit` API only supports list append/set add ([types.rs](/Users/kiril/src/git-meta/crates/git-meta-lib/src/types.rs:334)), so the caller cannot batch the full logical capture including `set`/`set_record`.\\n\\n- **P2 Batched list append has different storage side effects than `list_push`.** `SessionTargetHandle::list_push` goes through `Store::list_push`, which calls `list_push_with_repo(None, ...)` ([lists.rs](/Users/kiril/src/git-meta/crates/git-meta-lib/src/db/lists.rs:22)). But `Store::apply_edits` passes `self.repo.as_ref()` for `ListAppend` ([lists.rs](/Users/kiril/src/git-meta/crates/git-meta-lib/src/db/lists.rs:93)), so large batch-appended values can be written as Git blobs via `blob_if_large` ([mod.rs](/Users/kiril/src/git-meta/crates/git-meta-lib/src/db/mod.rs:264)) while the single-operation handle path stores the same value inline. That is a surprising API-behavior mismatch unless intentional and documented.\\n\\n- **P3 Batched set-add log semantics diverge from existing `set_add`.** Existing `set_add` logs the resulting full set via `encode_set_values_by_metadata_id` ([sets.rs](/Users/kiril/src/git-meta/crates/git-meta-lib/src/db/sets.rs:181)). Th